,"1403–1475":"1403–1475","1360–1402":"1360–1402","1360–1417":"1360–1417","by 1387  1st husband":"January 1387","about 1380":"about 1380","From 1387 to 1402":"from 1387 to 1402","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","1459":"1459","1403":"1403","1402":"1402","1369":"1369","Abt 1392":"about 1392","about 1407":"about 1407","1475":"1475","1386":"1386","1407":"1407","1417":"1417","Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Salt House, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Salthouse, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Coningsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Coningsby, Lincolnshire, England","Caister-on-Sea, Norfolk, England":"Caister-on-Sea, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Avenel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Avenell  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Avenell","meanings":["English: from the Old French personal name <i>Avenel</i>, a double diminutive of ancient Germanic <i>Avo</i>. The surname was later confused with   Averill  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Dev ."],"variants":[{"name":"Deborah","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘bee’ in Hebrew), borne by the nurse of Rebecca (Genesis 35:8) and by a woman judge and prophet (Judges 4–5) who led the Israelites to victory over the Canaanites. It has always been popular as a Jewish name. It was in use among Christians by the mid 16th century and was taken up by the Puritans in the 17th century, in part because the bee was a symbol of industriousness. Since then it has enjoyed enormous popularity, peaking in the 1960s. Among other famous bearers is the actress  Deborah Kerr  (  1921–2007 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice de Avenel was born about 1380, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Robert de Avenel, was 22 and her mother, Juliana Belknap, was 22. She married John Fastolf in 1403, in Lincolnshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. She died about 1407, in her hometown, at the age of 29."},"et":{"about 1380–about 1407":"umbes 1380–umbes 1407","1380–1407":"1380–1407","1370–1459":"1370–1459","1369–1417":"1369–1417","1386–Female":"1386–Surnud","1392–Male":"1392–Surnud","1403–1475":"1403–1475","1360–1402":"1360–1402","1360–1417":"1360–1417","by 1387  1st husband":"jaanuar 1387","about 1380":"umbes 1380","From 1387 to 1402":"1387 kuni 1402","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","1459":"1459","1403":"1403","1402":"1402","1369":"1369","Abt 1392":"umbes 1392","about 1407":"umbes 1407","1475":"1475","1386":"1386","1407":"1407","1417":"1417","Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Salt House, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Salthouse, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Coningsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Coningsby, Lincolnshire, England","Caister-on-Sea, Norfolk, E